snippet.textDisplay: Damnit. I'll watch it anyway because at this point supporting this gives them money to causeonomatopoeia  either cause the end of the world (because at this point Star wars has become the grandest cult) or will result in the most creative star wars film, but man this whole dichotomy between fans and the new trilogy has actually made me despise Star Wars. That says a lot because I love Star Wars. Directors need to stop trying to pander to crazy people because let's face it from all the reviews they spent way too much time trying to fix things from the last movie instead of actually, ya know, making a damn movie. So now no one is happy because no one likes a panderer. I mean look at what pandering has done. The first film was fine. Yeah we get it, it copys a new hope, piss off, if you're going to copy a movie that's a good one to copy. Fucking everyone has copied a new hope in some way or another because it's the quintessential hero's journey. But it was a good start. Everyone was fine until the hipster crowd started to hate like everything else that gains in popularity. So now everyone hates it for being a copy despite it being a solid star wars movie. So what happens? They get a guy who makes the movie a never ending cycle of twists! Look I can under stand how people don't like it. But I refuse to discredit some good scenes in the movie. Force ghost yoda was a good scene. Luke fading under the twin suns as his theme plays is a good scene. Rey being a nobody was a pretty good twist. The salt planet was a great design and probably the most star wars planet in recent memory. Hell the hyper drive into a fleet of imperial fleets was fun. But now people complain about the changes, and even worse Rian Johnson and Kathleen Kennedy had to piss off and also pander to the 2 most annoying groups of people. So now we are here. Trying again to fix the new trilogy, but at this point why bother fixing something something that's just going to be broken again. Yeah it's lazy and soulless because no matter what, someone new is just going to break it. Disney will ruin it because they want money. Fans will ruin it because it'll never be as good as their nostalgia. New fans will ruin it because they're normies who don't know what it means to be a fan. Directors don't care about legends or Lucas' original vision. Hell George Lucas for the longest time was the one who was responsible for breaking Star Wars. I love star wars. I hate what it's become. The fans, the writers, the directors, the critics, it's all just annoying at this point. It reminds me of this one thing in reviews that always pisses me off. People lately have this boner when it comes to tearing down paragons and pure evil villains in media. The protagonist is bad because they aren't flawed enough. The villain is bad because he isn't sympathetic. Piss off. We get it stories aren't realistic. God forbid anyone have fun anymore. Hell people keep bitching about how superman is boring because he's too much of a paragon, but guess what, every damn person who wanted to spice up the character and make him flawed and tragic made a movie that was a colossal flop. Hell I bet if we had a Superman movie that didn't pander to every edgy teenager who thinks they're a critic because he believes all heroes should be flawed and all villains should be sympathetic then we might get a good Superman movie. Paragons are unrealistic, but they are needed. Sometime we just need that paragon to uplift us. Gives us something to strive for. Hell it's definitely a good escape from reality where everything is already grey. I guess the point of that side tangent is not everything need to be this grand masterpiece to be enjoyed. Sometimes we should just turn our brains off and just see something for what it is, a nice little story. Hell I feel like we've forgotten that. When you look at the original Star Wars it's nothing that special. By all means it follows the Hero's journey to a tee. Even so, you could see the heart in it. It was creative, it was new, it was fun. Is Luke a Mary Sue? Yeah of course. Fuck you I love the whiny little bastard anyways. He's a good guy that I should aspire to be like, and I absolutely refuse to try and justify likeing a paragon to someone to the edgy teen critic.  That's the problem with the current Star Wars. Everyone is so hard pressed on pursuing a masterpiece. Creators will throw away their hearts to appease a scowling crowd who will only accept perfection. Well guess what? Because everyone complained about Rey being a Mary Sue, Rey fans wanted to justify liking her by calling out Luke, so now the new story tellers in their pursuit of "high art" turned Luke into a greasy hobo, and Rey into a nobody. Hell maybe Rey was supposed to be Obi Wan or even Qui Gon's daughter and that's why she was so strong in the force. Nope that's thrown out to shoehorn in some arbitrary flaws to appease those with "refined" taste.  Look none of this really matters. The way I see it, if you like the new cannon go nuts. Hell it's new star wars from new creators, and guess what you also have legends. I'll add this, it doesn't matter what is and isn't cannon. Fuck it the only real difference between fan fiction and "cannon" is if it can turn a profit for the IP so go nuts. It doesn't matter if it's cannon if you enjoy it. At this point we already know Lucas isn't the one involved so really it's all fan fiction anyways. Hell legends is basically fan fiction too. Just have some enjoyment with star wars for fucks sake. Look I get the whole "I criticize it because I love it" thing but honestly it just looks like an abusive relationship at this point. Tearing something down, name calling, and acting all pissy isn't criticism, it's just a tantrum. Hell no one grows from constant negative criticism, it just makes people into assholes. You want something to grow fucking at least point out the things that worked. Don't act all surprised when they throw out the good parts when all you've done is compain about how everything is shit. I'm thankful for the force awakens. For the longest time I kept being a Star Wars fan a secret because let's face it, being into nerdy things has only recently become an okay thing. I used to have a star wars t-shirt as a kid, it was one of my favorites and I was uncomfortable wearing it because everyone thought star wars was lame and for little kids. In retrospect it's funny that kids acted like they were too grown for kiddy things. Hell that generation probably spawned the 4 year olds playing CoD on XBox generation. So whenForce Awakens comes out it was great seeing so many people get excited over star wars again. It was good to be a star wars fan again. Now? Well it just speaks for itself. It's exhausting. Hell I can't even bring myself to enjoy things I like in new star wars media because it's just drowned out by people who prefer chants over coherent thoughts. At this point I just associate star wars with negativity because that's what my brain is conditioned to assume. Well fuck that! I've been a fan of Star Wars for too damn long to just give up hope. Everyone who wants to drag it down can get bent! Just because we've hit a bad spell of movies doesn't mean star wars is bad. Mandalorian is amazing. Clone Wars is amazing and getting a new season. Jedi Fallen order despite everything going against it was a good game and by an infinitely more bizarre miracle EA battlefront 2 has risen from the dead and became a good game. Hell we still have some good star wars movies. People still like rogue one, and pretty soon we're getting an Obi Wan movie. Hell as hated as the prequels were (at the time)  everyone loved Obi Wan, I'm sure It's the one thing that all Star Wars fans can agree on. So that's what I'll leave it on. Star wars isn't dead. We've just had a rough couple of years. Hell here's some advice to help star wars movies, hire Dave Filoni! Seriously he's the real reason people like the prequels. I bet you anything that if they put him in charge of remaking the sequels then nobody would be having this discussion. Hell just the prospect of him being in charge of a movie fills me with hope. I know this comment isn't going to change anything. It's just a rant culminated from years of annoyance, but I don't want to be some chanting hater or some delusional fanboy. At the end of the day I'm just a fan of Star Wars, and I want it to do well. I know I'm heading for disappointment with this movie, but just because this one is disappointing doesn't mean I should ruin future projects by more competent creators. Hell the Obi Wan project almost got canceled because people boycotted the Solo movie. It sucks that we have to justify that Star Wars is profitable, but hey in for a penny in for a pound. I want Star Wars to succeed and do better. There is still hope. So I'm happy ending it on that note. Also apologies to Jeremy Jahns, I did not mean to leave this essay here you just happened to be a reviewer I trust who happened to say the exact thing I was afraid you'd say about this movie.
